modName: Asa's Ultimate Grass And Tree Overhaul Comparison And Performance FPS Test
summary:
Folder containing all photos from my comparison plus single screenshots.
The comparison photos range from 5760x3242 to 1920x2160. Very large resolutions, as a result the photos in the description are very small, hard to focus on, so this folder contains all photos so you can zoom in as close as you want to compare them individually.
descriptionHtml:
All credits go to Bethesda, for making such a beautiful game and to the talented people who made these amazing mods for making this game infinitely more beautiful!

[url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/89378671@N07/14695783905/in/photostream/lightbox/]Use this link to view my photos on Flicker in full screen at full resolution in order[/url] Then navigate left or right. (Left clicking this link will NOT open a new tab)

[size=5]Introduction:[/size]
This is my attempt at making some comparison shots of several Grass/Tree/Landscape mods. Ones I personally like, some that are more popular, and some that maybe do not get enough love.
This comparison was NOT made to show how some mods are "better" or "worse" than others. That all boils down to your own personal tastes and the power of your computer.
The reason for this compilation was that it sounded like fun, I like to do fun things, I think you do too, and I had fun making them.
Please do not get upset if you do not see a mod that you think should, or deserves, to be showcased.
Please leave a comment and suggest anything, and I will gladly make more of these and include other mods. Tips and suggestions are extremely welcome!

[size=5]Information:[/size]
Under, or above, each photo will be a list of mods specific to that photo as well as average, minimum, and maximum framrates, also my opinions of the mod, and environmental settings. All mods have the recommended and necessary changes made to the skyrimprefs.ini, skyrim.ini, and etc...
Mods used in all photos are Skyrim Uber Textures, Real Roads, Static Mesh Improvement Mod, Natural Lighting And Atmospherics, Vivid Landscapes - Rocking Stones, Realistic Water Two + 2k ENB Textures + ENB Water Color, and Realvision ENB version 254a.

[size=5]My System Specs:[/size]
i5-3570k @ 4.2GHz
EVGA GTX780 OC, 5% Overclock
AS Rock Z77 Extreme4
8GB Corsair Ram, 1600MHz
Resolution is 1920x1080

[size=5]Other Info:[/size]
uGridsToLoad=7
[url=http://www.nexusmods.com/skyrim/mods/24364/?]AOF HD Tree LODs 4k[/url]
[url=http://www.nexusmods.com/skyrim/mods/3398/?tab=1&navtag=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.nexusmods.com%2Fskyrim%2Fajax%2Fmoddescription%2F%3Fid%3D3398%26preview%3D&pUp=1]Better Riften Tree LODs[/url]
[url=http://www.nexusmods.com/skyrim/mods/39394/?]Enhanced Distant Terrain 2[/url]
[url=http://www.nexusmods.com/skyrim/mods/30936/?]Realvision[/url] v 254a

[size=5][color=red]Disclaimer:[/color][/size]
My Reason for using Realvision instead of a nicer looking, more cinematic ENB, is because it is the most popular ENB and it is what most people are still using. It also gives a good framerate compared to other ENBs. I will not include framerates without an ENB because I believe you shouldn't even play Skyrim without an ENB. Add 10-15fps to the ones listed and that's where it should be at without an ENB. Add 5-8fps since you are more than likely on default uGridsToLoad.

Average Framerates for each mod are at the bottom of the page.
[color=red]DO NOT compare these framerates to your framerates, everyone's will be different depending on their system and the amount of mods they have.[/color]
[color=green]DO compare these framerates to the default number I have provided. That is the only accurate way of judging these framerates.[/color]

[url=https://flic.kr/p/o5RfT6][img]https://farm3.staticflickr.com/2936/14494725427_fd0f19987a_c.jpg[/img][/url]
Most of these grass mods are not compatible. Here is a good example. The beautiful trees of Skyrim Flora Overhaul 2.0 just do not mix well with Skyrim Bigger Trees. Skyrim Bigger Trees has its fair share of visual glitches by itself. It, mixed with SFO 2.0 makes the LODs look very odd and the textures are very stretched and ugly.

[url=https://flic.kr/p/op5R54][img]https://farm6.staticflickr.com/5554/14701073823_7becc80032_c.jpg[/img][/url]
However, in most cases, Skyrim Bigger Trees gives Skyrim a very different feeling, almost giving it a miniaturistic atmosphere, like you're inside a world blanketed in massive trees. Completely changes the feeling of the game. If you can get over the stretched textures and visual glitches at the bases of trees sticking out of hills that is.
